Case Study: Single-Cell RNA Sequencing Maps Endothelial Metabolic Plasticity in Pathological Angiogenesis

Kayla Interdonanto

Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center
Kayla.Morrell@RoswellPark.org

4 November 2022

Source: vignettes/hca-4c73d1e4-bad2-4a22-a0ba-55abbdbdcc3d.Rmd

Setup

Load useful packages

library(hcaCaseStudies)
library(hca)
library(dplyr)

Project information

Set the project id

project_id <- "4c73d1e4-bad2-4a22-a0ba-55abbdbdcc3d"

Display information about the project

project_information(project_id)
## Title
##   Single-Cell RNA Sequencing Maps Endothelial Metabolic Plasticity in
##   Pathological Angiogenesis
## Contributors (unknown order; any role)
##   Yonglun Luo, Katerina Rohlenova, Guy Eelen, Mieke Dewerchin, Liliana
##   Sokol, Peter Carmeliet, Dena Panovska, Steve Stegen, Kim D
##   Falkenberg, Xuri Li, Rene J Mclaughlin, Melissa García-Caballero,
##   Frederik De Smet, Abhishek Subramanian, Tine Van Bergen, Ami Day,
##   Yizhi Liu, Huanming Yang, Frank J T Staal, Patrik De Haes, Jian Wang,
##   Jermaine Goveia, Lucas Treps, Yingfeng Zheng, Laura P M H de Rooij,
##   Vincent Geldhof, Joanna Kalucka, Bernard Thienpont, Andreas Pircher,
##   Geert Carmeliet, Federico Taverna, Laure-Anne Teuwen, Stefan
##   Vinckier, Lars Bolund, Tobias K Karakach, Luc Schoonjans, Lin Lin,
##   Nadine Ectors, Shawez Khan, Lena-Christin Conradi
## Description
##   Endothelial cell (EC) metabolism is an emerging target for
##   anti-angiogenic therapy in tumor angiogenesis and choroidal
##   neovascularization (CNV), but little is known about individual EC
##   metabolic transcriptomes. By single-cell RNA sequencing 28,337 murine
##   choroidal ECs (CECs) and sprouting CNV-ECs, we constructed a taxonomy
##   to characterize their heterogeneity. Comparison with murine lung
##   tumor ECs (TECs) revealed congruent marker gene expression by
##   distinct EC phenotypes across tissues and diseases, suggesting
##   similar angiogenic mechanisms. Trajectory inference predicted that
##   differentiation of venous to angiogenic ECs was accompanied by
##   metabolic transcriptome plasticity. ECs displayed metabolic
##   transcriptome heterogeneity during cell-cycle progression and in
##   quiescence. Hypothesizing that conserved genes are important, we used
##   an integrated analysis, based on congruent transcriptome analysis,
##   CEC-tailored genome-scale metabolic modeling, and gene expression
##   meta-analysis in cross-species datasets, followed by in vitro and
##   in vivo validation, to identify SQLE and ALDH18A1 as previously
##   unknown metabolic angiogenic targets.
## DOI
##   10.1016/j.cmet.2020.03.009
## URL
##   https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1550413120301248?via%3Dihub
## Project
##   https://data.humancellatlas.org/explore/projects/4c73d1e4-bad2-4a22-a0ba-55abbdbdcc3d

Conventions

Statistics calculated locally use local.* for column names, e.g., local.cellCount.

project_filter <- filters(projectId = list(is = project_id))

## create `files2` with just the files needed for count-matrix
## analysis

files2 <- files1 |>
    filter(fileFormat == "csv")

Retrieve and cache locally all files needed to construct a gene x cell count matrix.

files3 <-
    ## the count data files
    files2 |>
    filter(grepl("Raw_counts.*_Data.csv", name))

file_path <-
    files3 |>
    files_download() |>
    setNames(files3 |> pull(name))

## join file path to appropriate components of `f`
count_matrix_files1 <-
    files3 |>
    left_join(tibble(
        fileId = files3$fileId,
        local.filePath = unname(file_path)
    ), by = "fileId")

We can extract some data from the files, e.g., cell and gene counts

## 'files' is the final, locally modified, version of file data
count_matrix_files <-
    count_matrix_files1 |>
    cell_count_csv() |>
    gene_count()

count_matrix_files |>
    select(name, local.geneCount, local.cellCount)
## # A tibble: 2 × 3
##   name                      local.geneCount local.cellCount
##   <chr>                               <int>           <int>
## 1 Raw_counts_mouse_Data.csv           17470           69079
## 2 Raw_counts_human_Data.csv           11990            6130

Since the count data wasn’t in gzip format we cannot calculate counts.

Count matrix

Create a dgCMatrix sparse matrix (defined in the Matrix package). Save it in the package cache for re-use across R sessions.

Similar steps can be used for the larger ‘mouse’ data in this experiment.

object_name <- "local.human.countMatrix"
if (!cache_exists(project_id, object_name)) {
    count_matrix_files |>
        filter(grepl("human", name)) |>
        count_matrix_csv() |>
        cache_add(project_id, object_name)
}
human_count_matrix <- cache_read(project_id, object_name)

class(human_count_matrix)[1] # sparse matrix
## [1] "dgCMatrix"
dim(human_count_matrix)      # genes x cells
## [1] 11990  6130
format(object.size(human_count_matrix), units = "auto")
## [1] "72.8 Mb"
